e diplomatic use of popular music was initially limited to such genres as jazz, the second half of the 20th century saw a growing presence of various popular genres in diplomatic contexts, including rock, punk, reggae, and hip-hop.This volume illuminates the interrelation of popular music and public diplomacy from a transnational and transdisciplinary angle. The contributions argue that, as popular music has been a crucial factor in international relations, its diplomatic use has substantially impacted the global musical landscape of the 20th and 21st centuries.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched - KU Select 2018: Frontlist Collection  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInternational relations and culture. 0aMusic and diplomacy. 0aMusicxPolitical aspects. 0aPopular musicxPolitical aspects. 4aCultural History. 4aDiplomacy. 4aHistory of the 20th Century. 4aHistory. 4aInternational Relations. 4aMusic. 4aMusicology. 4aPolitics. 4aPop Music. 4aPopular Culture. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aCultural History.  aDiplomacy.  aHistory of the 20th Century.  aHistory.  aInternational Relations.  aMusic.  aMusicology.  aPolitics.  aPop Music.  aPopular Culture.1 aBall, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayles, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Nicholas Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunkel, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunkel, Mario, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDíaz, Carlos Sa